  "query": "How do different methods of harvesting timber, such as selective logging and shelterwood harvesting, compare to clearcutting in their impact on moth diversity in US forests?",
  "relevant_summary": "Studies in US forests show that alternative harvesting methods generally have more favorable impacts on moth diversity compared to clearcutting. Shelterwood harvesting shows the most positive results, with one controlled, before-and-after study finding that macro-moth species richness was higher after shelterwood harvesting than after patch-cutting or clearcutting, and this richness was similar to thinned and unharvested forests. Another replicated, controlled study found that moth species richness recovered faster after shelterwood harvesting compared to group selection harvesting or clearcutting. Single tree selection harvesting (a form of selective logging) showed mixed results compared to clearcutting, with similar species richness in one study, but both selective logging and clearcutting had lower species richness than unharvested forests. Group selection harvesting, which involves harvesting small groups of trees, showed similar species richness to clearcutting forests but lower than unharvested forests, and recovery rates were similar to clearcutting but slower than shelterwood harvesting. Overall, shelterwood harvesting appears to be the most beneficial alternative harvesting method for maintaining moth diversity when compared to clearcutting.",
